    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Cross-shaped fixtures or painted marks in Catholic churches, most often on the walls or columns at the places consecrated with chrism during the consecration of the church. The symbolism for the crosses is laid out in liturgical treatises, such as the "Rationale" of Durandus; there are twelve consecration crosses to symbolize the twelve apostles.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079245/Catholic Encyclopedia [online] (2003-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Kruisvormige armaturen of geverfde markeringen in katholieke kerken, meestal op de muren of zuilen op de plaatsen die tijdens de consecratie van de kerk met chrisma zijn ingewijd. De symboliek voor de kruisen is uiteengezet in liturgische verhandelingen, zoals de 'Rationale' van Durandus; er zijn twaalf wijdingkruisen om de twaalf apostelen te symboliseren.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
